Indonesia Stocks: Bank Central Asia, Bumi Resources, Krakatau

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-04-29T09:25:54Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-29/indonesia-stocks-bank-central-asia-bumi-resources-krakatau.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  rose 10.69 points, or 0.3
percent, to a record 3,819.62. The gauge advanced 3.8 percent
this month.  PT Bank Central Asia (BBCA IJ), Indonesia’s biggest bank by
market value, declined 2.6 percent to 7,400 rupiah, the steepest
drop since Feb. 10. The bank’s rating was lowered to “neutral”
from “overweight” at Credit Suisse Group AG, which said the
company’s stock valuation was “demanding.”  PT Bumi Resources (BUMI IJ), Indonesia’s largest coal
producer, rose 2.2 percent to 3,425 rupiah, the highest close
since Sept. 25, 2008, after JPMorgan Chase & Co. raised Bumi’s
share-price estimate to 4,500 rupiah from 4,000 rupiah.  PT Indosat (ISAT IJ), Indonesia’s second-biggest telephone
company, advanced 2.9 percent to 5,350 rupiah, the steepest
increase since March 17. Indosat’s first-quarter net income
gained to 453.9 billion rupiah from 278 billion rupiah a year
earlier, the company said today.  PT Krakatau Steel (KRAS IJ),  Indonesia ’s largest producer
of the metal, fell 2.6 percent to 1,140 rupiah, the sharpest
decline since Jan. 31. Krakatau Steel said first-quarter net
income dropped 76 percent from a year earlier to 113.5 billion
rupiah as sales declined and costs increased.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  